<!-- ==Leeds 600==
One of 3 Leeds experimental single deck cars: 600 was converted from Sunderland 85, fitted with EP (electropneumatic) control and EMB bogies. Currently stored off site. 601 was an EP version of 602, and was externally very similar. This car was preserved, but was destroyed by arson shortly after. -->

==Leeds 602==
[[Image:Leeds 602.JPG|right|170px]]
'''Leeds 602''' is one of three experimental tramcars built for Leeds City Tramways, the others being [[#Leeds 600|Leeds 600]], and Leeds 601.  The tramcar is the only vehicle at Crich to use VAMBAC (Variable Automatic Multinotch Braking and Acceleration Control)<ref name=Official_fleetlist>{{cite web|url=http://www.tramway.co.uk/smx/cms/tramfleet2/|title=Official Fleetlist}}</ref>, and one of only 4 in the country (2 of which are at [[Blackpool tramway|Blackpool]], and the other being at the [[East Anglian Transport Museum]].

It entered service on the 1st June 1953<ref name=Official_fleetlist>{{cite web|url=http://www.tramway.co.uk/smx/cms/tramfleet2/|title=Official Fleetlist}}</ref>, and was built by Bus Manufacturer Charles H. Roe. Leeds 602 was withdrawn at the last ever ''"close of play"'' in 1957. The design of 602 owes a lot to the Glasgow [[#Glasgow 1282|Cunarders]] and [[#Glasgow 1297|Coronations]], due to the fact that the General Manager of Leeds at the time was A.B.Findlay, who did at one stage produce drawings of a single-decker Cunarder. Findlay used these ideas to build two identical prototypes (601 and 602), and Leeds 602 was fitted with VAMBAC equipment under the Bow Collector. In addition, all it's fittings are elctrical, making it a very complicated tram!<ref name=602_BTO>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/602.html|title=British Trams Online 602 Profile}}</ref><ref name=602_TSW>{{cite web|url=http://train.spottingworld.com/Leeds_City_Tramways_VAMBAC_No._602|title=TrainSpottingWorld 602 Profile}}</ref>

602's service life was spent working the Hunslet Route around leeds - the blind for which can be seen in the picture - and it was here until the end of it's working life, when it was acquired for preservation at the National Tramway Museum.<ref name=602_BTO>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/602.html|title=British Trams Online 602 Profile}}</ref><ref name=602_TSW>{{cite web|url=http://train.spottingworld.com/Leeds_City_Tramways_VAMBAC_No._602|title=TrainSpottingWorld 602 Profile}}</ref> Leeds 601 was also preserved, but was destroyed soon after in an arson attack.

Once at Crich it was used in service between 1967 and 1972, before it's first workshop attention in 1973. It saw further used in 1974-5, and returned to the workshop in 1977. It was back in the fleet for the 1979-80 seasons, before having a third bout of workshop attention in 1986. Following this it had a longer operational life in 1987-1995, but it was finally withdrawn due to the discovery of a leaking roof. It was resurrected on a limted-use basis for the Tramathon in 2003 <ref name=03_tramathon>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/tramathon03.html|title=Tramathon 2003}}</ref>, and then it was withdrawn to have attention to it's leaky roof.  <ref name=602_BTO>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/602.html|title=British Trams Online 602 Profile}}</ref> This was finally fixed, and a long-needed repaint was undertaken. <ref name=TMS_Crich_forum>{{cite web|url=http://tmscrich.iphpbb.com|title=TMS Forum}}</ref> It returned for the Tramathon and Enthusiast's Day in 2005, and was used for 6 days in 2006.<ref name=602_TSW>{{cite web|url=http://train.spottingworld.com/Leeds_City_Tramways_VAMBAC_No._602|title=TrainSpottingWorld 602 Profile}}</ref> One of which was the enthusiast's day, which allowed the oppurtunity to ride both a bus and tram built by Charles H. Roe. <ref name=2006_enthu_day>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/enthusiastsday06.html|title=Enthusiast's Day 2006 Report}}</ref> The tram has not been used since<ref name=BTO_fleetlist>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/crich.html|title=British Trams Online Fleetlist}}</ref>, and now languishes in the depot next to [[#Halle 902|Halle 902]].<ref name=602_TSW>{{cite web|url=http://train.spottingworld.com/Leeds_City_Tramways_VAMBAC_No._602|title=TrainSpottingWorld 602 Profile}}</ref>



<!-- ==Liverpool 869== 
[[Image:Green Goddess.jpg|right|170px]]
This tram is in a Green and white livery, and is affectionately known as the Green Goddess. One of Liverpool's fleet of Bogie streamliners (there were also 4 wheel versions), it was later sold on to Glasgow, from where it was bought. Fitted with EP control, is often used for UDEs (Ultimate driving experiences, i.e. one-day tram driving courses for members of the public, equivalent to the "footplate experience" of steam railways) -->

